BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:i9Sxmr8Ab-XN2pO6o7GQN
SUMMARY:K-Nexus: Hierarchical Gene-to-Cell AI Modeling for Perturbation-Ind
	uced Transcriptomic Shift Recovery
DTSTAMP:20260627T134757Z
DTSTART:20260708T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Zihan Zhao  Masters Candidate  Thesis Defense
	  Department: Electrical and Computer Engineering  Predicting cellular res
	ponses to genetic and chemical perturbations can accelerate therapeutic di
	scovery by reducing experimental screening. However\, predicting post-pert
	urbation gene expression\, particularly for unseen perturbations\, remains
	 challenging because response signals are sparse\, cellular responses are 
	heterogeneous and often unpaired\, and responsive genes are obscured by do
	minant non-responsive genes. We propose K-Nexus\, a hierarchical gene-to-c
	ell framework that formulates perturbation response prediction as distribu
	tion-shift recovery over responsive genes. K-Nexus encodes perturbation-co
	nditioned regulatory interactions at the gene level and aggregates them in
	to cell-level representations that preserve response heterogeneity. Attent
	ion-based gene importance\, response-aware weighting\, and group-based dis
	tributional training focus learning on genes driving perturbation-induced 
	changes. K-Nexus also incorporates perturbation and regulatory graphs to c
	apture functional relationships between targeted genes and downstream path
	ways. Across three single-cell perturbation benchmarks\, K-Nexus outperfor
	ms state-of-the-art baselines\, particularly in responsive-gene distributi
	onal alignment\, demonstrating improved recovery of expression shifts and 
	generalization to unseen perturbations.  &#160\;  (Department : Electrical
	 and Computer Engineering)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu/live/events/432801-k
	-nexus-hierarchical-gene-to-cell-ai-modeling-for\n\nFrom Rice University -
	 Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/live/events/432801-k-nexus-hierarchical-gene-to
	-cell-ai-modeling-for
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
BEGIN:VEVENT
UID:sgw9dDK-1NEHmv9e1uxgt
SUMMARY:O⁺ Transport from the Ionospheric Cusp to the Inner Magnetosphere: 
	A Global MHD and Test Particle Study
DTSTAMP:20260627T134757Z
DTSTART:20260708T170000Z
DESCRIPTION:&#160\;  Speaker: Yiwen Zhu  Doctoral Candidate  Thesis Defense
	  Department: Physics &amp\; Astronomy  Location: Herman Brown Hall HBH 25
	4  During geomagnetic storms\, ionospheric oxygen (O⁺) can become a signif
	icant constituent of Earth's ring current\, the current system whose build
	up drives the main-phase depression of the surface magnetic field. The pol
	ar cusp is a principal source\, feeding O⁺ outflow into the magnetotail lo
	be\, but how much of this oxygen is delivered inward to the inner magnetos
	phere\, and how it is energized along the way\, remain poorly quantified\,
	 in part because the transport spans scales that no single model resolves.
	  &#160\;  In this thesis\, we follow ionospheric oxygen from the cusp to 
	the ring current using a global magnetohydrodynamic simulation (GAMERA/MAG
	E) coupled one-way to a test-particle tracer (CHIMP). Because MAGE include
	s an inner-magnetosphere model\, it produces and resolves the mesoscale bu
	rsty bulk flows (BBFs) of the plasma sheet that drive earthward transport.
	 With it\, we identify a "drop-down" channel that controls the delivery to
	 the inner magnetosphere: the dipolarization field carried by these flows 
	pulls cusp oxygen from the lobe down to the equatorial plasma sheet\, and 
	the ions that experience it form a more efficient ring-current injection c
	hannel than those that convect down the tail unaided. Within an adiabatic 
	(guiding-center) framework\, we decompose the energy gain along the transp
	ort into its Fermi\, betatron\, and E×B contributions and quantify each\, 
	and we characterize where the oxygen departs from adiabatic behavior.  To 
	put these results on a quantitative footing\, we weight the test particles
	 by an O⁺ outflow rate computed directly from the simulation's MHD variabl
	es. For a real storm\, this lets us quantify the absolute amount of cusp o
	xygen delivered to the inner magnetosphere and follow its contribution to 
	the ring current through the storm\, showing that a portion of the cusp ox
	ygen is accelerated to ring-current energies and adds to the ring-current 
	population. As a separate diagnostic\, we characterize the energy and pitc
	h-angle phase-space distributions\, f(K\, α)\, of the cusp oxygen at sever
	al locations along the transport and at ring-current entry\, mapping how t
	he population is energized and reshaped as it moves inward.  Finally\, we 
	step back to the cusp itself. Forecasting where the cusp lies from the ups
	tream solar wind is operationally important\, yet no data-driven model has
	 provided the cusp position directly. We develop a machine-learning model\
	, gradient-boosted decision trees trained on DMSP spacecraft cusp crossing
	s\, that predicts the cusp location from solar-wind and interplanetary-mag
	netic-field conditions\, offering a fast alternative to a full simulation.
	  Together\, these results advance two distinct fronts. The simulation and
	 test-particle study closes a missing link in the cusp-to-ring-current pat
	hway: it resolves how cusp oxygen reaches the inner magnetosphere\, decomp
	oses how the ions are energized along the way\, and quantifies their absol
	ute contribution to the storm-time ring current. The cusp machine-learning
	 model is a separate\, data-driven product: a fast predictor of the cusp l
	ocation from the upstream solar wind\, suited to operational use where a f
	ull simulation is impractical. Both improve how the entry of ionospheric h
	eavy ions into the inner magnetosphere can be modeled and anticipated.  (D
	epartment : Physics &amp\; Astronomy)\n\nhttps://events.rice.edu/event/433
	274-o-transport-from-the-ionospheric-cusp-to-the-inner\n\nFrom Rice Univer
	sity - Open to the Public
URL:https://events.rice.edu/event/433274-o-transport-from-the-ionospheric-c
	usp-to-the-inner
GEO:29.7174;-95.4018
LOCATION:Herman Brown Hall
X-CALRIPPER-SOURCE:rice-public-events
CATEGORIES:Rice University - Open to the Public
TRANSP:TRANSPARENT
DURATION:PT1H
END:VEVENT
